Friedman's works include monographs, books, scholarly articles, papers, magazine columns, television programs, and lectures, and cover a broad range of economic topics and public policy issues.[16] His books and essays have had global influence, including in former communist states.[17][18][19][20] A 2011 survey of economists ranked Friedman as the second-most popular economist of the 20th century, following only John Maynard Keynes.[21] Upon his death, The Economist described him as "the most influential economist of the second half of the 20th century ... possibly of all of it".[22]
